detailed description': This feature combines the total cholesterol level and Body Mass Index (BMI) to assess the combined impact of these two elements on heart disease risk. It might help capture both the impact of obesity and cholesterol levels, which are known to influence cardiovascular health.  \n'brief description': An index combining cholesterol and BMI for heart disease risk assessment.  \n'relevant': ['totchol', 'bmi']  ", "'new_feature': 'cholesterol_bmi_ratio'  \n'detailed description': This feature represents the ratio of total cholesterol level to Body Mass Index (BMI). It may help in understanding the relationship between cholesterol levels and body fat, potentially indicating how efficiently the body processes cholesterol based on the amount of body mass. This can be particularly relevant in assessing cardiovascular risk.   \n'brief description': Ratio of total cholesterol to BMI.  \n'relevant': ['totchol', 'bmi']  ", "'new_feature': 'diabetes_pressure_interaction'  \n'detailed description': This feature is an interaction term formed by taking the product of the diabetes status and the systolic blood pressure. It reflects the combined impact of diabetes and high blood pressure on cardiovascular health, potentially uncovering individuals at greater risk.  \n'brief description': Combined effect of diabetes and systolic blood pressure.  \n'relevant': ['diabetes', 'sysbp']  ", "'new_feature': 'blood_pressure_glucose_ratio'  \n'detailed description': The 'blood_pressure_glucose_ratio' is calculated by dividing the sum of systolic and diastolic blood pressure by the glucose level. This ratio provides insight into the combined effect of blood pressure and glucose, highlighting potential cardiovascular stress due to hypertension and glucose metabolism.  \n'brief description': A ratio assessing combined blood pressure and glucose levels.  \n'relevant': ['sysbp', 'diabp', 'glucose']  ", "'new_feature': 'metabolic_syndrome_score'  \n'detailed description': The metabolic syndrome score is a composite index created to quantify the combined impact of obesity (BMI), hypertension (systolic and diastolic blood pressure), and glucose levels on the risk of metabolic syndrome, which can contribute to coronary heart disease. The score is calculated as (BMI * sysbp * diabp * glucose) / 1000.  \n'brief description': A composite score reflecting the risk of metabolic syndrome based on BMI, blood pressure, and glucose.  \n'relevant': ['bmi', 'sysbp', 'diabp', 'glucose']  ", "'new_feature': 'bmi_pressure_product'  \n'detailed description': This feature is calculated by multiplying the Body Mass Index (BMI) with the average of systolic and diastolic blood pressure. High BMI and blood pressure are significant cardiovascular risk factors, and their combination can provide a nuanced perspective on the patient's overall health risk.  \n'brief description': Product of BMI and average blood pressure.  \n'relevant': ['bmi', 'sysbp', 'diabp']", "'new_feature': 'cholesterol_bmi_ratio'  \n'detailed description': This feature represents the ratio of total cholesterol level to body mass index (BMI). A higher ratio might suggest higher cholesterol levels relative to body size, which could indicate potential cardiovascular issues.  \n'brief description': Ratio of total cholesterol to BMI.  \n'relevant': ['totchol', 'bmi']", "'new_feature': 'cholesterol_bmi_ratio'  \n'detailed description': This feature represents the ratio of total cholesterol to BMI, providing insight into the relationship between a patient's cholesterol level and their body mass. Higher ratios might indicate potential cardiovascular issues related to cholesterol that are not apparent from BMI alone.  \n'brief description': Ratio of cholesterol to BMI.  \n'relevant': ['totchol', 'bmi']  "]
